Articles.Content:
What graphics card would you use for playing KSP?

I use a Nvidia Geforce gt 420 and I feel like its struggling, getting fps drops when I look at the planet from orbit.

8 GB ram, KSP uses 4 gb of it and my cpu is well, totally fine with it.

What graphics card would you use for playing KSP?

I use a Nvidia Geforce gt 420 and I feel like its struggling, getting fps drops when I look at the planet from orbit.

8 GB ram, KSP uses 4 gb of it and my cpu is well, totally fine with it.

Have you tested the CPU and GPU? Is, so, how exactly?
By basic ksp testing I guess, it starts to get choppy after setting higher graphics, Im only assuming dealing with graphics is a gpu job. Arent calculations made with cpu?

By basic ksp testing I guess, it starts to get choppy after setting higher graphics, Im only assuming dealing with graphics is a gpu job. Arent calculations made with cpu?

That is the basis, yes, but testing the problem really is needed before trying to fix it. You made a good start by playing with the graphics settings, that certainly points towards the graphics card. I would suggest you open up the Windows Task Manager (or better yet, get Process Explorer) to view CPU usage and a program like GPU-Z or Afterburner to view GPU performance while gaming. A comparison of the graphs should quickly reveal what and how much of a disparity there is between the two.

Do you know how much fps you get?

Will do those on my free time, Im on mobile, but KSP greatly helps. My fps is unknown, but ksp clock is flashing green/yellow in orbit, yellow while staring at the planet and red at launches. I blame new launch smokes.

If you are going to look for a new gpu, it would be helpful to know what you have in your computer most importantly the cpu and the power supply wattage. Without knowing that, I would recommend the 750 ti for about $150 since it only has a slightly higher power consumption than your 420 and doesn't need any additional power connector, so it should be compatible with your computer.
If I'm reading that log right then your GPU is the bottleneck with all those 99% loads. Removing EVE should give you an increase in frame rate.

Sorry for asking more, but could you post a screenshot of both Task Manager and the GPU-Z usage graph next to each other for the same stretch of gameplay? Uploading is simply via something like Imgur. Comparing those is the interesting bit.

Oh yeah, but, in a few hours from now.

I have a question though, when I alt tab away from the game, it looks like my GPU usage turns to normal levels again.

How can I get both task manager and GPU-Z on my screen while I have KSP on? Should I attempt to be really fast so the graphs stay revelant before getting overridden by desktop-state? How many seconds do you think would be enough for revelant, helpful data?

By uninstalling EVE it seems that performance increased by a minimum 50% too. I suddenly dont want clouds in my game..

Oh yeah, but, in a few hours from now.

I have a question though, when I alt tab away from the game, it looks like my GPU usage turns to normal levels again.

How can I get both task manager and GPU-Z on my screen while I have KSP on? Should I attempt to be really fast so the graphs stay revelant before getting overridden by desktop-state? How many seconds do you think would be enough for revelant, helpful data?

By uninstalling EVE it seems that performance increased by a minimum 50% too. I suddenly dont want clouds in my game..

The graphs should not refresh terribly fast, so tabbing out should not be a huge issue. Just play a minute or so until you get the behaviour you feel is relevant. If that is all the time, a short bit should be enough.

By uninstalling EVE it seems that performance increased by a minimum 50% too. I suddenly dont want clouds in my game..

That very definitely points towards the GPU, but let us see.

Make sure in task manager that you right click on the cpu graph and select "change graph to" an select "logical processors". The reason for this is that ksp's physics calculation can only be done on one thread and this will show us how much of each thread is being used as opposed to your total cpu use.
Understood, that will also stop graphing other programs, so no interference right?

Understood, that will also stop graphing other programs, so no interference right?

It should not stop graphing other programs, Task Manager/Process Explorer runs independently of other programs.
I dont think chrome/task manager and GPU-Z can take up a lot of processor power anyway so the graphs will be mainly KSP (again, only guesses)

I dont think chrome/task manager and GPU-Z can take up a lot of processor power anyway so the graphs will be mainly KSP (again, only guesses)

Oh, now I get what you mean. It would be better to close off what you can, so preferably no Chrome. Task Manager uses very little, and GPU-Z a little, but that is fine.
Your CPU is not the thing struggling. It's your GPU. Wish people would stop with 'you don't need a good graphics card for KSP' it's like saying you don't need a good CPU for battlefield.

This was a kerbal X launch

I have a reason mkay

How did the CPU graphs look further down? The GPU looks like it has a tough job, as it is almost fully loaded, but if that goes along with KSP loading up one whole core, both are having trouble. The total graph does not give it all the information we need there, as 1 core out of 4 fully loaded only looks like 25%.

You want the statuses of the each core? I can do that

Edited June 13, 2015 by Feradose
You aren't maxing out any of the cores, so it does look like your bottleneck is your gt 420.

You want the statuses of the each core? I can do that

http://i.imgur.com/0dKwRzj.png

It looks like the GPU is the culprit indeed. Sorry for making you jump through all these hoops, but I think it is better to make sure and give sound advice than to rush it. There is no use in people buying things they do not actually need.

- What is your budget for a card?

- What make and model PSU do you have?

- Do you want to play any other games?

- At what:

--Resolution

--Settings

--Fps

do you want to play KSP and/or other games?

My recommendation for a low cost gpu would be the 750 ti for about $150 like I said earlier. If you want to spend a little more and your power supply can handle it then you may want to also look at the r9 270x for about $185 or the gtx 960/r9 280x for about $200.
well I plan on playing ksp at highest settings with visual mods, and that should be able to play any games fine enough for me
